Gene and metabolite correlation

Loading datasets

library(tidyr)

Gene dataset

gene_df = read.csv(file="../raw_data/Quantifications_and_functional_annotations.tsv",
                   sep="\t",
                   stringsAsFactors = TRUE,
                   nrow = 10000,
                   na.strings = c("NA", "-"))

Environment variables

If we want to use the KEGG_ko instead of the preferred names, set the following to True.

Use_kegg = FALSE

After loading the gene dataset, we remove all columns except those containing the number of reads and the columns called “Prefered name” which seems to contain names for matched genes.

if (Use_kegg) {
  Column_of_interest = 47
} else {
  Column_of_interest = 44
}

dim_raw = dim(gene_df)[1]
gene_df = gene_df[,c(2:35,Column_of_interest)]

## Computing relative abundance
for (i in 1:34){
  sum_col = sum(gene_df[,i])
  if (sum_col != 0){
    gene_df[,i] = gene_df[,i]/sum_col
  }
}


if (Use_kegg) {
  gene_df = separate_rows(gene_df,all_of( "KEGG_ko"), sep = ",", convert = TRUE)
  
  functions_name_corresp = read.csv("../ressources/KEGG_ko_final.csv", sep = ";")
  
  gene_df$KEGG_ko = functions_name_corresp$Definition_function[match(gene_df$KEGG_ko, functions_name_corresp$Code_function)]
  gene_df$KEGG_ko = as.factor(gene_df$KEGG_ko)

}

gene_df = drop_na(gene_df)
print(paste0((dim(gene_df)[1]/dim_raw)*100, "% of the rows have been conserved (",dim(gene_df)[1],")"))
[1] "10.59% of the rows have been conserved (1059)"
head(gene_df)
colnames(gene_df) = c(paste0("Piglet_", seq(34)), "Gene")
gene_df = gene_df[c(dim(gene_df)[2], 1:(dim(gene_df)[2])-1)] ## Putting the "gene" column first

The relative abundances are then computed.

We then aggregate the duplicated genes by row.

gene_df = aggregate(gene_df[-1], by = list(gene_df$Gene), FUN = sum)
colnames(gene_df)[1] = "Gene"

gene_names = levels(gene_df$Gene) ## Saving the list of genes names for later
head(gene_df)

Finally, the data.frame is translated.

gene_df = as.data.frame(t(gene_df)) ## Transposing the data.frame 
colnames(gene_df) = gene_df[1,]
gene_df = gene_df[-1,]
gene_df$Piglet = rownames(gene_df)

head(gene_df)

Metabolite dataset

metabo_df = read.csv(file="../raw_data/HOLOPIG METABOLITES clean.csv",
                    sep=";",
                    stringsAsFactors = TRUE,
                    na.strings = "NA",
                    check.names = F)
metabo_df = subset(metabo_df, select = -c(Group)) ## Removing "Group" column
#metabo_df = metabo_df[,1:100]

metabo_df$Piglet = paste0("Piglet_",as.character(metabo_df$Piglet)) ## Renaming piglets
metabo_names = colnames(metabo_df[-1]) ## Saving the name of metabolites for later

head(metabo_df)

Merging both dataframe

data = merge(gene_df, metabo_df, by = "Piglet", all = T) ## Merging dataframes by the name of the piglet.

data[,-1] = as.numeric(unlist(data[,-1])) ## Converting characters to numeric
data = Filter(function(x)!all(is.na(x)), data) ## Removing empty columns

rm(list=c("gene_df", "metabo_df"))

head(data)

Correlating data data.frame

cor_data = as.data.frame(cor(data[, -1], method = "spearman"))
head(cor_data)
cor_data$metabolites <- rownames(cor_data)
cor_data = cor_data[c(dim(cor_data)[2], 1:(dim(cor_data)[2])-1)]

head(cor_data)
library(reshape2)

melted_data = melt(cor_data, id = "metabolites") ## Melting the data.frame

melted_data = drop_na(melted_data) ## Removing empty columns
melted_data$metabolites = as.factor(melted_data$metabolites) 
colnames(melted_data)[2] = "genes"

## Removing genes in metabolite column and reverse.
melted_data = subset(melted_data, metabolites %in% metabo_names & genes %in% gene_names)
melted_data = droplevels.data.frame(melted_data)

rm(list=c("cor_data"))

head(melted_data)

We then export the current dataframe.

write.table(melted_data, 
            file = "../refined_data/metabo_X_gene_cor.tsv",
            col.names = TRUE,
            row.names = FALSE,
            sep="\t")

Filtering metabolites and genes

Filtering on correlation values

In order to do that, we filter the melted_data data frame to keep rows if the correlation value is more than the threshold or less than the negative threshold.

thres_keep = 0.6

filtered_melted_data = melted_data %>% subset(melted_data$value <= -thres_keep | melted_data$value >= thres_keep)

filtered_melted_data = droplevels.data.frame(filtered_melted_data)

rm(list=c("melted_data"))
head(filtered_melted_data)

We then subset melted_data using thresholds on both genes and metabolites. For that we will plot the distribution of correlation means.

library(ggplot2)

We plot the threshold on histograms to see where it lands

print(paste("Number of correlation with a value superior to the threshold (", thres_keep, ") : ", sum(filtered_melted_data$value >= thres_keep)))
[1] "Number of correlation with a value superior to the threshold ( 0.6 ) :  449"
print(paste("Number of correlation with a value inferior to the inversed threshold (", -thres_keep, ") : ", sum(filtered_melted_data$value <= -thres_keep)))
[1] "Number of correlation with a value inferior to the inversed threshold ( -0.6 ) :  232"

Filtering on correlation p-values

selected_genes = levels(filtered_melted_data$genes)
selected_metabo = levels(filtered_melted_data$metabolites)

tmp_data = data[,c(selected_genes, selected_metabo)]

library("psych")
## suppressWarnings is here to not show warnings about standard deviation being null (which slows down the function)
cor_res = suppressWarnings(corr.test(tmp_data[,-1], method = "spearman", ci = F))
cor_pval = as.data.frame( cor_res$p )
cor_pval$metabolites <- rownames(cor_pval)
cor_pval = cor_pval[c(dim(cor_pval)[2], 1:(dim(cor_pval)[2])-1)]

melted_pval = melt(cor_pval, id = "metabolites") ## Melting the data.frame

melted_pval = drop_na(melted_pval) ## Removing empty columns
melted_pval$metabolites = as.factor(melted_pval$metabolites) 
colnames(melted_pval)[2] = "genes"

melted_pval = subset(melted_pval, metabolites %in% metabo_names & genes %in% gene_names)
colnames(melted_pval)[3] = "pvalue"
melted_pval = droplevels.data.frame(melted_pval)

filtered_melted_pval = subset(melted_pval, pvalue >= 0.05) # Keeping only significative results

rm(list=c("melted_pval", "tmp_data"))
head(filtered_melted_pval)
filtered_melted_data = merge(filtered_melted_data, filtered_melted_pval, 
                             by = c("metabolites", "genes"))

We will plot the distribution of correlation values.

hist(abs(filtered_melted_data$value), 
     breaks = 40)

We then export the filtered data.frame.

write.table(filtered_melted_data, 
            file = "../refined_data/filtered_metabo_X_gene_cor.csv",
            col.names = TRUE,
            row.names = FALSE,
            sep=";")

Creating the heatmap

filtered_melted_data_ordered = order(filtered_melted_data[,-c(1,2)], decreasing = TRUE)
filtered_melted_data = filtered_melted_data[filtered_melted_data_ordered[1:100],]

ggplot(filtered_melted_data, aes(gene, metabolite, fill= value)) +
  geom_tile(colour = "white", size = 0.5)+
  scale_fill_gradientn(name = "Correlation coefficient",# definition of the color gradient.
                       #trans = "log10", #chosing a logarythmic color scale
                       breaks = c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5 ,1), 
                       labels = c(-1, -0.5, 0, 0.5 ,1),
                       #na.value = "#43A3B9",# plotting the 0 in the lowest color of the gradient
                       colours = c("#43A3B9",  "#D0EC97", "#FFFFDF", "#FD945D", "#DC4E51", "#370303"),
  )+
  
  scale_x_discrete(expand=c(0, 0))+ # Removing blank space between data and X axis
  labs(fill="correlation coefficient", # Setting legend and title name
       title = "Correlation coefficients between genes and metabolites")+
  theme_grey(base_size=12)+ # Setting the base font size
  theme(line = element_blank(), # Removing the lines in between the boxes
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank(), # Removing ticks on X axis
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, face="bold.italic", size = 30), # Removing X labels
        axis.text.y = element_text(face="bold.italic", size = 30), # Setting Y labels to bold
        axis.title.x = element_blank(), # Removing X axis title
        axis.title.y = element_blank(), # Removing Y axis title
        panel.border=element_blank(), # Removing space between figure and panel
        legend.text=element_text(face="bold", size = 15), # Customizing legend font
        plot.title = element_text(face="bold", size = 50), # Same with main title
        legend.title = element_text(face="bold", size = 15), # Same with legend
        legend.key.size = unit(2, "cm"), # Setting the legend scale
        strip.text.y = element_text(angle = 0, face = "bold", size = 15),
        strip.text.x = element_text( face = "bold", size = 15))
        
  #facet_grid(rows = vars(filtered_data$kingdom), 
             #cols = vars(factor(filtered_data$cat, 
                                #levels = c("Control", "Colistin"))),
             #scales = "free",
             #space = "free")

#SAVE HEATMAP  
scale = 200 # Set the scale for the exported image

ggsave(filename = "../export/heatmap_correlation_VA.png",
       plot = last_plot(),
       width = 40*scale,
       height = 30*scale,
       units = "px",
       dpi=200)

Correlation graph

The purpose of this section is to create a correlation graph between genes and metabolites that are well correlated.

First, we will show the most correlated variables :

filtered_melted_data$abs_cor = abs(filtered_melted_data$value)
new_order = order(filtered_melted_data$abs_cor, decreasing = T)
filtered_melted_data = filtered_melted_data[new_order,]
head(filtered_melted_data, n = 10)

Based on the best correlated metabolites and genes, we can create a correlation plot.

## Loading libraries
library(ggplot2)
library(hrbrthemes)

## Setting the X and Y columns to show
x_col = "VPS13"
y_col = "glucosamine-6-phosphate"

##
ggplot(data, aes(x = data[,x_col]*100, y = data[,y_col]*100))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = lm, color = "red", se = F, show.legend = T)+
  labs(title = paste0("Correlation graph between ", x_col, " and ", y_col),
       x = paste0("Relative abundance of ", x_col," (%)"),
       y = paste0("Relative abundance of ", y_col," (%)"))+
  theme_grey(base_size=12)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face="bold", size = 15))

We can export the previous plot.

scale = 200 # Set the scale for the exported image

ggsave(filename = paste0("../export/correlation_graphs/",x_col,"_X_",y_col,".png"),
       plot = last_plot(),
       width = 16*scale,
       height = 9*scale,
       units = "px",
       dpi=200)
